<!--  DIRECTIONS  -->
<ol>
	<li>If using fresh clams see step 7 for preparation, otherwise continue to step 2.</li>
	<br />
	<li>Open cans of clams and strain juice into measuring cup. Add water until combined mixture equals three cups. Heat until simmering.</li>
	<br />
	<li>In large pot, saute garlic and onions in oil and butter until onions are transluscent. Add carrots and celery and saute for three or four minutes.</li>
	<br />
	<li>Add heated clam juice and water, potatos, bacon, and bay leaves. Bring to a boil. Reduce heat and simmer 1 to 1&frac14 hour.</li>
	<br />
	<li>Add tarragon, thyme, salt (if using), and pepper. Stir into soup.</li>
	<br />
	<li>Remove from heat and let cool about 10 minutes. Stir in clams and warmed milk. Spoon into bowls and add parsley.</li>
	<br />
	<li>If using fresh clams: rinse clams under cold water and put them in a steamer. The steamer should have plenty of water. Bring to a boil and steam the clams no more than four or five minutes. Remove the steamed clams and rinse under cold water again. Save the steamer water and use it in step 4. Note: it is important to rinse the clams after steaming so they do not get overcooked and become tough. Continue to step 3.</li>
	<br />
</ol>


